The programmer wants `zero` to set the caller's variable to 0, but it doesn't work. What is the bug?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

void zero(int n) {
    n = 0;
}

int main() {
    int x = 99;
    zero(x);
    std::cout << x << '\n';  // expected: 0, actual: 99
    return 0;
}
```
